INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'cb9acc79-08a9-41f8-96af-35198dde1fed',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$PyTorch + XGBoost — Gradient Boosting on Frozen Encoder Embeddings$escape$,
  $escape$When your PyTorch encoder produces high-dimensional embeddings (256–2048-dim), XGBoost often outperforms a fully-connected head on small-to-medium tabular targets. The pattern: freeze the encoder, extract features, hand off to gradient boosting for the final decision boundary.

Extract with `model.eval()` + `torch.no_grad()`, convert via `.detach().cpu().numpy()` — XGBoost's `DMatrix` takes the raw array directly. Set `"device": "cuda"` in params to keep compute on the same GPU your PyTorch model occupies, eliminating host-device round trips.

For hyperparameter tuning, `xgb.cv()` with `early_stopping_rounds` beats manual grid search — it finds optimal `num_boost_round` without overfitting. Key params on dense embeddings: `max_depth` (3–6), `eta` (0.01–0.1), `subsample` + `colsample_bytree` (0.6–0.9 prevents over-reliance on correlated embedding dims).

Feature importance via `get_score(importance_type="gain")` reveals which embedding dimensions drive predictions — a practical diagnostic for encoder collapse or redundancy in contrastive learning setups. This hybrid is especially strong for transfer learning on small labeled datasets where a trainable MLP head would overfit.$escape$,
  $escape$import torch
import xgboost as xgb

model.eval()
with torch.no_grad():
    feats = model.encoder(x_tensor.to(device)).detach().cpu().numpy()

dtrain = xgb.DMatrix(feats, label=y_np)
params = {
    "objective": "binary:logistic",
    "max_depth": 4,
    "eta": 0.05,
    "subsample": 0.8,
    "colsample_bytree": 0.8,
    "device": "cuda",
    "eval_metric": "auc",
}
cv = xgb.cv(params, dtrain, num_boost_round=300, nfold=5, early_stopping_rounds=15)
best_round = int(cv["test-auc-mean"].idxmax())
bst = xgb.train(params, dtrain, num_boost_round=best_round)
print(bst.get_score(importance_type="gain"))$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
